itorial process of the Hebrew Psalter, concluding that after the Babylonian exile, distress was more strongly associated with divine discipline and displeasure, whereas before the exile it was more associated with declarations of innocence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aBible. 4aStudy/Old Testament. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Studies / Old Testament.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertGorgias Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060675108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertReligious Studies Gorgias eBook Packagez978311071684940uhttps://doi.org/10.31826/978146323708040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781463237080423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781463237080/original  a978-3-11-060675-1  Gorgias Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-071684-9  Religious Studies Gorgias eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK